Hey thanks for this question, to expand on this -

Inference Labs will operate two complementary networks to accelerate decentralized AI verification and commercialization.

**Subnet 2** serves as an open participation proving ground for zkML and computational verification technologies. It provides a neutral benchmarking layer where various proving systems can compete and innovate, while incentivizing critical adjacent tasks like model distillation, circuit optimization, and decentralized infrastructure growth. Subnet 2 ensures the ecosystem develops objective performance standards that will be essential as zkML adoption scales.

**Sertn** is a separate, commercial-grade verification layer for proprietary model operators. It allows operators to protect their intellectual property while offering cryptographically verified inference services to decentralized networks. Operators bond collateral and produce proofs to guarantee execution integrity, enabling trustless service provision without sacrificing privacy. Beyond AI, Sertn extends to broader Web3 use cases, including rollup verification, incentive design, and decentralized marketplace coordination.

Together, Subnet 2 and Sertn position Inference Labs as both the leading research hub for verifiable computation standards and the commercialization platform for trustless AI and decentralized computing services.

@. HudsonGraeme [τ, β] I noticed that after my report was closed, the vulnerability I submitted has since been fixed on your end. This clearly shows the issue was valid and required remediation. Closing the report while still applying a fix feels unfair and inconsistent with the principles of responsible disclosure.  report immunefi id 53167 please re-review my report thanks 😌

Hello, thanks for your bug report. To provide context since this was surfaced here, you identified that the telegram invite link on https://omron.ai was expired. We did update our link, but due to an internal ticket and not this report. The reason your report was closed is due to it's technical validity. Our ImmuneFi bug program clearly lists the in-scope impact to be:

> Taking over broken or expired outgoing links, such as: Social media handles, etc.

Due to the nature of how Telegram generates group invite links, it is not possible to overwrite or hijack an existing join link and thus there is no attack vector exposed due to the link being invalid; the link permanently remains in an "invalid" state. Since no proof of concept was provided demonstrating any security vulnerability, the report was closed.

We appreciate all reports that come in and encourage you to submit others along with PoC demonstrations of their validity. We take security seriously and continue to accept, patch and payout reports that demonstrate valid and in-scope security risks.
